%% CVerify — lifecycle of a single authenticated API request
%%
%% Sources verified:
%%   docs/architecture/reverse-engineered/GROUND-TRUTH.md
%%     §3 middleware order (Program.cs:610-623), cookie auth (Program.cs:506-533),
%%        TokenService.SetTokenInsideCookie:139
%%     §2 the three coexisting authorization mechanisms
%%     §5.1 CORS "AllowFrontend" hardcodes localhost:3000 in ALL environments
%%   CVerify/deployment/nginx/cverify.conf (edge behaviour before the app)
%%
%% Middleware order is drawn EXACTLY as registered. SessionValidationMiddleware
%% sits BETWEEN UseAuthentication() and UseAuthorization() — that ordering is
%% load-bearing and is the reason it can reject a token whose session chain was
%% revoked by refresh-reuse detection.

sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    participant B as Browser
    participant N as nginx (host, :443)
    participant RL as 1. RequestLoggingMiddleware
    participant EX as 2. ExceptionHandlerMiddleware
    participant CO as 3. CORS ("AllowFrontend")
    participant SH as 4. SecurityHeadersMiddleware
    participant RA as 5. RateLimiter
    participant AU as 6. Authentication (JwtBearer)
    participant SV as 7. SessionValidationMiddleware
    participant AZ as 8. Authorization
    participant C as Controller action
    participant DB as PostgreSQL / Redis

    B->>N: GET https://api.cverify.com.vn/api/... <br/>Cookie: access_token=<JWT HS256>
    Note over N: TLS termination · limit_req cverify_general 10r/s<br/>(cverify_auth 5r/m on login/register/forgot/reset)<br/>adds X-Real-IP / X-Forwarded-For / X-Forwarded-Proto<br/>HSTS · nosniff · DENY · Referrer-Policy · Permissions-Policy<br/>NO Content-Security-Policy is set
    N->>RL: proxy_pass 127.0.0.1:5247 (path unchanged, "/api" prefix kept)

    RL->>EX: begin request scope, correlation id, timing
    Note over EX: wraps everything downstream;<br/>unhandled exceptions become a normalized error response

    EX->>CO:
    Note over CO: policy "AllowFrontend" hardcodes<br/>http://localhost:3000 and http://127.0.0.1:3000<br/>in ALL environments including Production

    CO->>SH:
    Note over SH: application-level security response headers<br/>(in addition to nginx's)

    SH->>RA:
    Note over RA: ASP.NET Core rate limiter, IP-partitioned.<br/>Real client IP depends on ForwardedHeaders being<br/>configured — see CODE_CHANGES_REQUIRED.md

    RA->>AU:
    Note over AU: JwtBearerEvents.OnMessageReceived UNCONDITIONALLY sets<br/>context.Token = Request.Cookies["access_token"].<br/>An Authorization: Bearer header is therefore IGNORED.<br/>Cookie: HttpOnly, Secure (non-dev), SameSite=Lax, Path=/,<br/>Domain = Auth.CookieDomain (shared parent domain)
    AU-->>B: 401 if the cookie is missing, expired (15 min) or the signature fails

    AU->>SV: ClaimsPrincipal
    SV->>DB: look up the session / token chain
    Note over SV: runs BETWEEN UseAuthentication() and UseAuthorization().<br/>Rejects tokens whose session chain was revoked by<br/>TOKEN_REUSE_DETECTED during refresh rotation.
    SV-->>B: 401 if the session is revoked or invalid

    SV->>AZ: validated principal + session
    Note over AZ: three coexisting mechanisms:<br/>(1) [Authorize(Roles="SUPER_ADMIN,ADMIN")] — Recovery controllers only<br/>(2) [HasPermission("...")] — the permission string IS the policy name,<br/>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;resolved by PermissionPolicyProvider -> PermissionHandler<br/>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;with colon-segment wildcard matching<br/>(3) org-scoped checks are NOT here — they run imperatively inside the action
    AZ-->>B: 403 if the policy is not satisfied

    AZ->>C: endpoint invocation
    C->>C: _authService.AuthorizeAsync(userId, orgId, permission)<br/>scope string "permission:name:SCOPETYPE:scopeId";<br/>an ORGANIZATION grant implicitly covers child WORKSPACE scopes
    C->>DB: read / write (business change + outbox row in ONE transaction)
    DB-->>C:
    C-->>EX: result
    EX-->>RL: response
    RL-->>N: response (+ timing log)
    N-->>B: HTTPS response

    Note over B,DB: NOT on this path — verified absences:<br/>• no API gateway, no service mesh, no WAF, no CDN<br/>• no global fallback authorization policy, so a controller with<br/>&nbsp;&nbsp;no auth attribute (EmailTestController, SystemController) skips<br/>&nbsp;&nbsp;steps 6-8 entirely and reaches the action anonymously<br/>• AppPermissions.cs is an empty class — every [HasPermission]<br/>&nbsp;&nbsp;passes a raw string literal (9 distinct values in total)
